{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_grafton_ver01/data/sn85007266/00415668995/1907101701/0148.xml":{"full_text":"The Wallace Miner\n_ _ _ _ _\n*i\nPabllaM Brwr ThunSay lqfU\u00bb\nMiser Printing Pnbliahing Company\nH. W. C. JACKSON, Mgr.\nact of CongreM of March 3, 1870.\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICK\nOne year. In advance.\nSix months, in advance.\nMingle ent y.\nFOREIGN\u2014Canada and all countries in the\npostal union, one year, In advance...\nADVERTISING RATES\nOlaglay\nK\n2 fiO\n{JJ\n1 Inch, per month.\n3 India*. per month..\n3 Incite*, per month.\n4 inchei. per utonth.\n6 incite*, per month.\n0 incite*, per month.\n8 to 30 Inches, per Inch, per month\nQuarter pace, per month.30 00\nHalf pace, per month.35 00\ntee, per month.. MOO,\n4 tVwumh'^Vwiwn n r ind.;^Mrjo*im\"hes:\n$is 8 w?*e ft '$a> ,ch: <,UMrt r lU: Ul< l\nRaaSara and Lagal Natleaa\nOne intertion, lo cent* a line, and oaeh subee\nquent insertion 5 cent* a line.\n8 liU\n4 26\n6 UI\n70\n1-a\nLOCAL STOCK QUOTATIONS\nThe Miner has been somewhat in\na quandary as to what to do about\npublishing quotations on milling\nstocks. So long as both the Wallace\nand Spokane exchanges were run\nning there was nothing for us to do\nbut publish their prices no matter\nhow little respect we had for them\nor how inaccurate or unfair we\nbelieved them to lie. The respons\nibility was not on us. Now, luiw\nJ\n.Oh the Wslta,\nd\u00abband\u00abt and the Spokane\nchange basing its prices on sellers'\na\nand buyers options, we feel that we\nA a\nmust eliminate bpokanc quotations\nand yet our readers will look to us\nto give them exact prices at which\nthey can do business.\nI nder these circumstances an i d\nafter giving the matter deep consul -1\neration we have decided to !*e r, '-1\nsponsible for the quotations our\nsedves since the responsibility u\nour readers finally rests on us and\nwe will therefore publish only one\ntable of prices\u2014the local market\u2014\nwhich will take due cognizance of\nSpokane transactions without ae\never\nt\ncepting them in all cases as tlte\nlast and only authoritative word on\nthe subject.\n1 he quotations which will ere\nafter appear in our market report\nwili therefore lie the prices which\naccording to the information we\nhave gleaned from all sources seem\nto us Ui aecuraU'ly represent the\nprices which sellers will tuke for\ntheir stocks and which buyers are i\nIt is about time that the plain,\nunvarnished truth was being told to I\nthe business men of Wallace. So\nfar from being \"the pluckiest, I\npersistent, most optimistic\nthe Mis-1\nreading the I\nMincr's editorial and news columns\n.he, number among them large\nmajority of peasimists and moss- j\nhacks who got cold feet as Boon asjl\u00abt\nlead and copper fell in price. Many\nof them have never spent a dollar of!\n\noffering.\ni\nMOSSBACKS IN BUSINESS\nmost\nlot of business men,\nsoulian calls them after\nM\nas\nthur ottu money to at \\ertise t e\nf' T.Tn ,t Urc r 1\nfmttia t ic fn m pm* i u 1 l!e\nice m the Coeur d Alenes. 1 hey have\n\nlieen content to sit tight through\na\nbad times and gor'd and cop\nthen pr-m-ntage of the country\n>r< f^? ,eri\nThey are today bow.,hog the\nfact that prices for metal are lower\ny at .1 i\nthan they were; that the bottom\n\nhas apparently fallen out of the\ni i i .v. *t i i\nstock market and that the local\nbusiness outlook is not so good as it\nwas. What are they doing to rem\nedy any of the evils they complain\nof\n\nThe prices of the metals are of\ncourse, beyond their control, but\nthey could at least help to publish\nabroad the fact that they are much\nhigher than any body expected a\nfew years ago; are not likely to go\nlower and will probably go much j\nhigher again.\nAs to the stock market, they can j\nstill do much to revive it though\nthey could have done vastly more'\nin the recent past. Still there's no j\nuse crying over spilt mUk and if.\nthey were what the Missoulian cred-j\nits them with being they would put\ntheir hftnd8 in their tm\nlittle advertising and the market\nwould -soon take care of itself.\nI If the business outlook is hot so\nbright as it was it is largely their\nown fault. There has not been and\nill n \"t be any material curtailment\nin production, or even in profits,\nof a permanent character,\nus many men are at work as\nI ever at the same wages. If there is\nlack of confidence they could restore\nit by taking the proper steps to put\nj the facts of the situation before the\nJust\n\nK\nI public.\nJL\nfiO\ni The panic in the copper market\nis undoubtedly title to the folly of\n{JJ II. H. Rogers who believed that it\nwas in his power absolutely to die-1\ntate the price which consumers\nmust pay. This is not the first\ntime that such an error has been\n00\n00\nmat, e with regard to copper but\nthat Mr. Rogers should have fallen\ni into it is a distinct surprise. It\n4\nj goes to show that even th\u00a9 head of\nthe great Standard Oil is not in-;\n1 fallible in the realm of finance.\nToo great success had evidently\nswelled his idea of his own power\nj till he blundered like any tyro.\nThe panic will, however, soon nbate\nand with his interference elimin\nated the law of supply and demand\nwill quickly restore workable condi\ntions and a price probably in the\nneigh 1 tor hood of 15 cents\u2014a highly\nremunerative figure for the produc\nor.\nliU\n26\nUI\n70\ni\nj'\nj\nj\ni\nj v\nNow is the auspicious time to\nThe\nj i>trtet llM aff ed b\n\nthe fall in the price of copper, lead\n\nand zinc than any other mining\nju Unfted and\nj ()n]y requir0( this fnct to f)e brougllt\nj foH iWy t(J the atlention 0 f investors\ni to turn a stream of money in this!\nj u rection that has been flowing f or\n-1 ye)m towardH Nevada to the great\naclvantag0 of tlmt community.\nj 0ne th j ng an d only one thing will\ni, rinK it a K) ut\u2014advertising. It was\nj blipjt that brought prosperity to!\n\n\nj\nthe deserts and deserted towns of\nNevada. Intelligent and persistent\nj publicity would bring still greater\nprosiierity to the Coeur d'Alenes.\nW( n >t somelKidy take the lead and\norgftnize U) educat(} the eafltern\npeople about Idaho and the Coeur\nI d'Alenes?\nI lh- _i_an- j\nNot all the business men of\nWallace are pessimists and moss\nbacks by a long way. Among them\nare some that are certainly entitled\nto lie classed as the \"pluckiest, most\ni persistent and most optimistic of\nbut they constitute a small\nThe Miner takes off its\nhut to them one and all even if they!\nhave ot s fit to support if in\nI its efforts to advertise the town and\nStrict. Among the more notable\nI of them are: Herman J. Rossi, H.\nF. Samuels, B. F. O'Neil, James\nF. McCarthy, Jerry Hayes, W. J.\nI B^ker, E. H. Moffit, Kratzer\nMcKinnis, James Howarth andi'\nJ\u00bbh.> H. Nnrdquiat. They are not\nftfraid to take a chance; they i\u00ab^er\nasjl\u00abt \u00abP and they meet a loss with a j\n\u00abnnle and another effort that\nusually achieves success.\n\nt>\ni men,\nminority.\n__\nThere are sinister reports in cir\n!\u2122l\u00bbtK.n Of Malting in connection!\nw ;th the (irmiouglm' purchase\nal 7 i\nthe Red Canyon placers in Wyom\nn A\nThe truth will probably be j\nlo lhal )le p urc haaem 1\nlemw|v s The p robabn I\nity of this was pointed out months i\nfctingublW ini\nal\nengineer in an article in the Mining\nn\nand Scientific Press. He said then,\n\nt,iat t lc Greenoughs' method of:\ni\nj\nThe Miner is generally recognized 1\ntesting and valuing the gravel was\nfaulty and amateurish.\noutside of the Coeur d' Alenes as\nthis country's best advertisment,\nnex t to its record for production;\nan( j profits.\npeople at home could be brought to\nrealize this fact. Thank gxxtdncss\na f ew 0 f them have done so and\nhave been supporting the paper\nnobly, otherwise the burden of\ndoiny all the country's advertising I\nof cost to the beneficiaries\nwould have been too heavy for us.\n\nThe people of the Coeur d'Alenes, j\neach one acting for himself, can\nsquander money for advertising in\nWe wish a few more\nhigher price if the law of supply\nand demand, aided by the Dingley\ntariff, is left to work out its\nthe eastern papers without accom\nplishing any adequate result, while\nthe same amount of money con\ntributed with enlightened selfish\nness to a common fund for adver\ntising the country would bring the\nsame people, indirectly, big\nturns on their investment. Who\nwill organize them to do it?\nre\nI iPad is scarce abroad, none too\nabundant at home and sure to\ncommand four cents a pound or a\nown\nresults. There is therefore nothing\ni for the load producer to worry\nabout unless it is these Napoleons\nof finance who every ohee in a\nwhile butt into the market, boost\nprices and end up by going broke.\nmmwHmmi\nWhen the Press reprinted\ngarbled version of that editorial\nfrom the Missoulian which\n\nreproduce on another page it\nfully eliminated ali reference to the\nMiner which had inspired it. Does\nj the Press think that it or anything\nit or its owners has ever said or\ndone entitles it to be considered\n\"pluckiest, most persistent or most\noptimistic?\na\nwe\ncare\n\nFrom the annual report of the\nGranby company, which owns a\ngreat low grade copper mine in\nsouthern British Columbia, we\nlearn that the cost of producing\ncopper was 8.115 cents a pound.\nGranby ore averages much less in\ncopper (and silver too) than Snow\nStorm. What need then to worry\nabout a price for copper of 14\ncents or more?\n\ni Twenty years ago when our\nj pioneers were only guessing about\nthe district's mineral resources,\nJ any assurance of four cents a pound\nt\u00bbr lead, with railroad and existing\n*\u00abcilitie\u00ab for mining thrown in,;\nwould have been considered\ni godsend. Today we 'practically\nhave it but it seems to be unappre- j\na\neiateci.\nj\nAlent couldalwft y 9 be8ure that\nthp y would aB bi P riw8 for\ntheir lead and copper an those now\nru,in minin in this countr 5'^\nwould be a cinch. Yet the pros\npects are, so far as the most fore\nsighted man can nee, that they will\naverage muc h higher.\nAt the annual meeting of the\nSpokane Stock Brokers' association i\nheld this week the conservative 1\nelement which wanted to close the\nexchange was outvoted by the rad\n\u00ab<\u00bb1 element which elected all the\nofficers.^ Another case of \"too bad\"\nJoe Keane would sa y,\nM\nThe Miner cannot expect support\nf\u2122 mossback busmess men but\nJt would a PP reclate flU P^ rt of\nenterprising business and min\nn n J* n 0 tire jiommuriity and\nll 11\no^rves 1 i\nThf Miner expects to hear that\nof the leading business men\nIf the producers of the Coeur\nof Wallfice have got sore because\nthe Miner called them mossbacks.\nW.I1, th., don't h\u00bbft to put the\nof|e\u00abp on unlew it belong to them,\nmmmmm\nto d rti R\u2122ry bwincm man\nknow. that. Then wh, don't the\na ace public get together and\nadyertwe \u00bb,\u201ee of the \u00abm\u00abl thing,\nthev have to sell?\nu,ty *\"^11\n\nThe way to sell a good article is\nDon't worry about the price off\nlead when you have none to sell.!\nThe producers are getting more for\nit now than they have averaged for!\n20 years while they have been\npiling up millions.\nnd P' e,lt y buyers at remuner-!\native P rice8 wben you bav<> t,ie j\n9ed mmmama\n\nTh<> S I8* lin( xcha u* e \"W have\nf\u00b0 pp d h h ort nd wa8h 8ale8\nw ,nPr not f rom\nMl 0U 1 Wl1 have to 1x5 8hoWn\nOrfr fl.00 a Yw\nThftt ifl wh&t thc Mlner cogtfl\nIt gives you all the Coeur d'Aleid\nmining news.\ni\nGet busy your mine and pro\nduce lead or copper. You will\nOIVIOEND RECORD OF COEUR d'ALENE MINES\ni TOTAL TO\nRATE\nTOTAL\nTHI*YEAR\nRAID TUI* MONTH\nEROM JAN. 1. '07|\nTO BERT *0. '117 I\nFaID by former ovnfju\nINOT INCLUDED IN TOTAL)\nRAID RRlOJt TO TOTAL RAID\nJAN. 1, 1906 LAST YEAR\nOOMRANY OR MINE\nDATE I AN OCNT\nHunker Hill And Sullivan Co.\nfederal M.4 N.Co. four mined..\nHercules (tMtimAte.il.\nKeel a\nSnow Storm..\nFrkco.\nI'itMlNirx.\nMllCOI'**.\nMonitor.\nIs .(V*.(00\n6.640.000\n2.O0.U0C\n1.420.